HEADWORD: Hemorrhage
<hw>Hem"or*rhage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>haemorrhagia</ets>, Gr. <grk>a"imorragi`a</grk>; <grk>a"i^ma</grk>
blood + <grk>"rhgny`nai</grk> to break, burst: cf. F.
<ets>h⟦eacute⟧morragie</ets>, <ets>h⟦eacute⟧morrhagie</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Any discharge of blood from the blood
vessels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The blood circulates in a system of closed tubes, the
rupture of which gives rise to hemorrhage.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hemorrhagic</ent>⟦br⟧
